%I A396959 #5 Jun 17 2026 22:18:52
%S A396959 3,5,6,11,29,35,49,52,53,58,60,67,80,85,86,100,133,153,165,185,194,
%T A396959 222,236,242,243,245,250,267,273,285,291,292,294,326,335,336,345,351,
%U A396959 363,364,402,415,433,448,449,450,458,461,479,482,612,617,629,632,672,690
%N A396959 Numbers k such that (Omega(A046086(k)) + m, Omega(A046087(k)) + m, Omega(A020882(k)) + m) forms a primitive Pythagorean triple for some integer m >= 0, where Omega is A001222.
%C A396959 Let x = Omega(A046086(k)), y = Omega(A046087(k)), z = Omega(A020882(k)); the sequence consists of those k for which there exists an integer m >= 0 such that (x + m, y + m, z + m), after sorting, forms a primitive Pythagorean triple.
%C A396959 There exists at most one such m. Indeed, after sorting x <= y <= z we have z < x + y; defining f(m) := (x + m)^2 + (y + m)^2 - (z + m)^2 gives f'(m) = 2*m + 2*(x + y - z) > 0 for all m >= 0, so f is strictly increasing and has at most one nonnegative root.
%C A396959 The condition that (x + m, y + m, z + m) forms a primitive Pythagorean triple leads to the quadratic equation m^2 + 2*(x + y - z)*m + (x^2 + y^2 - z^2) = 0. Its discriminant is d = 8*(z - x)*(z - y), and eliminating m shows that a necessary and sufficient condition is that (z - x)*(z - y) is twice a perfect square, hence lies in A001105.
%C A396959 This condition, (z - x)*(z - y) = 2*s^2, corresponds to factorizations of integers of the form 2*s^2; compare A211513, which counts such factorizations without additional constraints. Among these factorizations, those corresponding to Pythagorean triples are exactly the ones for which the two factors can be written in the form 2*v^2 and (u - v)^2. Thus Pythagorean triples arise precisely from those factorizations of 2*s^2 in which the square factors can be separated in this way. In particular, this shows that the parametrization of primitive Pythagorean triples arises naturally from a special class of factorizations of 2*s^2. The number of such factorizations corresponding to a given difference is given by A379830.
%C A396959 For primitive Pythagorean triples x = u^2 - v^2, y = 2*u*v, z = u^2 + v^2 one has z - x = 2*v^2 and z - y = (u - v)^2, giving d = (4*v*(u - v))^2, so the discriminant is always a square in the target configuration.
%C A396959 Empirically, two types of solutions dominate. In the vast majority of cases one has (x, y, z) = (n, n + 1, n + 2), which implies (z - x, z - y) = (2, 1) and hence (z - x)*(z - y) = 2, corresponding to the minimal case. These solutions always yield, after translation, the primitive Pythagorean triple (3, 4, 5).
%C A396959 Rare exceptional cases occur where larger gaps appear between x, y, z; for example (x, y, z) = (1, 2, 10) gives (z - x, z - y) = (9, 8) and (z - x)*(z - y) = 72 = 2*6^2, producing nontrivial primitive Pythagorean triples. The examples listed correspond to the smallest index k producing each indicated triple, that is, the minimal index for which (x + m, y + m, z + m) yields that triple.
%C A396959 Empirical computations up to k <= 10^6 show that only four types of factorizations (z - x, z - y) occur, namely (2, 1), (8, 1), (9, 2), and (9, 8), even though the equation (z - x)*(z - y) = 2*s^2 admits infinitely many solutions. Equivalently, only the values s = 1, 2, 3, and 6 occur in the relation (z - x)*(z - y) = 2*s^2, and it is not known whether further values of s occur.
%C A396959 Since primitive Pythagorean triples have hypotenuse u^2 + v^2, all odd prime divisors of the hypotenuse are congruent to 1 mod 4, so no prime congruent to 3 mod 4 can occur. Up to A020882(k) <= 10^8, the target triples are (3, 4, 5), (5, 12, 13), (8, 15, 17), and (20, 21, 29), corresponding to the smallest observed primes congruent to 1 mod 4 (namely 5, 13, 17, 29). It is not known whether infinitely many such k exist, or whether infinitely many primes congruent to 1 mod 4 arise in this way; the additional constraints involving Omega suggest that this may be quite restrictive.
%C A396959 This sequence is complementary in spirit to A396955-A396958: whereas those sequences start from Gaussian prime powers p^n and study the induced additive structure of their components, here one starts from additive prime-factor counts and detects when they can be shifted to realize a Pythagorean structure.
%H A396959 Felix Huber, <a href="/A396959/b396959.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A396959 3 is a term since (Omega(A046086(3)) + m, Omega(A046087(3)) + m, Omega(A020882(3)) + m) = (Omega(8) + m, Omega(15) + m, Omega(17) + m) = (3 + m, 2 + m, 1 + m) = (5, 4, 3) for m = 2, and sorting gives the primitive Pythagorean triple (3, 4, 5).
%e A396959 977 is a term since (Omega(A046086(977)) + m, Omega(A046087(977)) + m, Omega(A020882(977)) + m) = (Omega(2071) + m, Omega(5760) + m, Omega(6121) + m) = (2 + m, 10 + m, 1 + m) = (21, 29, 20) for m = 19, and sorting gives the primitive Pythagorean triple (20, 21, 29).
%e A396959 59209 is a term since (Omega(205335) + m, Omega(327488) + m, Omega(386537) + m) = (8 + m, 1 + m, 9 + m) = (12, 5, 13) for m = 4, and sorting gives the primitive Pythagorean triple (5, 12, 13).
%e A396959 117796 is a term since (Omega(A046086(117796)) + m, Omega(A046087(117796)) + m, Omega(A020882(117796)) + m) = (Omega(387585) + m, Omega(687232) + m, Omega(788993) + m) = (8 + m, 1 + m, 10 + m) = (15, 8, 17) for m = 7, and sorting gives the primitive Pythagorean triple (8, 15, 17).
%p A396959 with(NumberTheory):
%p A396959 g := proc(n) option remember;
%p A396959     Omega(abs(n));
%p A396959 end proc:
%p A396959 f := proc(N)
%p A396959     local l, m, k, x, y, z;
%p A396959     l := [];
%p A396959     for m from 2 while m^2 + 1 <= N do
%p A396959         for k from 1 to m - 1 do
%p A396959             if igcd(m, k) > 1 then next end if;
%p A396959             if (m - k) mod 2 = 0 then next end if;
%p A396959             z := m^2 + k^2;
%p A396959             if z > N then break end if;
%p A396959             x := m^2 - k^2; y := 2*m*k;
%p A396959             l := [op(l), [z, max(x, y), min(x, y)]];
%p A396959         end do
%p A396959     end do;
%p A396959     sort(l, (u, v) -> u[1] < v[1] or (u[1] = v[1] and u[2] < v[2]));
%p A396959 end proc:
%p A396959 A396959List := proc(N) # All terms with A020882(n) <= N
%p A396959     local d, k, l, m, q, r, s, t, x, y, z;
%p A396959     l := f(N);
%p A396959     s := [];
%p A396959     for k to nops(l) do
%p A396959         t := sort([g(l[k][1]), g(l[k][2]), g(l[k][3])]);
%p A396959         x := t[1]; y := t[2]; z := t[3];
%p A396959         q := 2*(x + y - z); r := x^2 + y^2 - z^2; d := q^2 - 4*r;
%p A396959         if d >= 0 and type(sqrt(d), integer) then
%p A396959             for m in [(-q + sqrt(d))/2, (-q - sqrt(d)) / 2] do
%p A396959                 if type(m, nonnegint) then
%p A396959                     if (x + m)^2 + (y + m)^2 = (z + m)^2 then
%p A396959                         if igcd(x + m, y + m, z + m) = 1 then
%p A396959                             s := [op(s), k];
%p A396959                             break
%p A396959                         end if
%p A396959                     end if
%p A396959                 end if
%p A396959             end do
%p A396959         end if
%p A396959     end do;
%p A396959     s
%p A396959 end proc:
%p A396959 A396959List(4325);
%Y A396959 Cf. A001105, A001222, A020882, A046086, A046087, A211513, A379830, A386306, A396955, A396956, A396957, A396958.
